						<b>WOLFOWITZ</b>
<br>

<br>
If the World Bank evangelizes one thing it's good governance, free of corru=
ption. Ironic then that its chief, Paul Wolfowitz, finds himself at the cen=
tre of a nepotism scandal. He has apologised and accepted the blame for his=
 involvement in negotiations over his girlfriend's pay whilst she was worki=
ng alongside him.=20
<br>

<br>
But will that be enough to save his job? He's already made enemies along th=
e way for controversial decisions he's taken at the Bank. So will this scan=
dal just precipitate a resignation many have wanted to see for some time?=
=20
<br>

<br>
<b>RUSSIAN REVOLUTION</b>
<br>

<br>
The man who claims he made Putin now wants to break him, in no uncertain te=
rms. Boriz Berezovsky has called for an uprising against Putin and his remo=
val from government. He has insisted he doesn't mean through force, but thr=
ough a people's revolution. We will talk to the Kremlin tonight and see if =
they're trembling in their boots.
<br>

<br>
<b>NUCLEAR EXPLOSION</b>
<br>

<br>
Well, not exactly. But an explosion of power stations which will probably l=
eave the world with another 70 over the next two decades.=20
<br>

<br>
Our film tonight charts the remarkable transformation of a rogue nuclear st=
ate which defied weapons inspectors to do its own thing - much to the chagr=
in of the west. That country? India. It is now the largest democracy in the=
 world, and one that is well on the road to being self sufficient in provid=
ing cheap, clean energy. Is there a lesson to be learnt from this? Or do th=
e ghosts of Chernobyl still loom too large?
<br>

<br>
Join me tonight at 10:30pm
<br>

<br>
Emily=20=20=20=20
<br>
=20=20
